BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wassaic-project-2027-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260701
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260702
SUMMARY:Deadline: Wassaic Project 2027 Residency Open Call
DESCRIPTION:The Wassaic Project runs a single 2027 Artist Residency open ca
 ll covering both the Winter Residency (January to April 2027) and the Summ
 er Residency (June to September 2027) in Wassaic\, New York. Residents rec
 eive a private studio (about 100 square feet in winter\, 200 to 300 square
  feet in summer)\, a private bedroom in a shared house with common spaces 
 and kitchen\, and access to a wood shop in both seasons and a print shop i
 n summer. Programming includes open studios\, group studio visits\, and in
 dividual artist talks. The residency operates on a sliding scale fee of US
 D 0 to 900 per session\, with the organization covering roughly USD 5\,000
  per person through donor and grant support. The open call is open to indi
 vidual artists\, collaborative teams\, groups of two or more\, and applica
 nts through the Family Residency program. This is the residency program\, 
 distinct from the separate Summer Exhibition open call.\n\nOrganisation: W
 assaic Project\nLocation: Wassaic\, New York\, USA\nAward: Studio space an
 d a private bedroom in a shared house provided\; the organization covers a
 pproximately USD 5\,000 per person through donor and grant support. Reside
 ncy fee on a sliding scale of USD 0 to 900 per session. USD 25 application
  fee (waivers available for financial hardship)\nDuration: Sessions range 
 from roughly 2 to 4 weeks within the Winter (Jan-April 2027) or Summer (Ju
 ne-Sept 2027) programs\n\nMore: https://www.wassaicproject.org/apply
URL:https://www.wassaicproject.org/apply
LOCATION:Wassaic\, New York\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:loghaven-artist-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260716
SUMMARY:Deadline: Loghaven Artist Residency
DESCRIPTION:Loghaven Artist Residency offers practicing artists time\, spac
 e\, and resources on ninety wooded acres in Knoxville\, Tennessee. Fellows
  stay in five rehabilitated historic log cabins with access to purpose-bui
 lt studio space. Each Fellow receives an USD 850 weekly living stipend\, a
  travel subsidy on a sliding scale from USD 400 to 800\, up to USD 200 in 
 materials shipping reimbursement\, and covered room and board. Residencies
  run from 2 to 6 weeks across sessions scheduled throughout 2027. The prog
 ram is open to artists at any career stage working in architecture\, dance
 \, interdisciplinary art\, music composition\, theater\, visual art\, and 
 writing\, including collaborative groups of up to nine people. Applicants 
 must be at least 21\, live more than 120 miles from Knoxville\, and be eli
 gible to work legally in the US\; international artists and degree-seeking
  students are not eligible.\n\nOrganisation: Loghaven Artist Residency\nLo
 cation: Knoxville\, Tennessee\, USA\nAward: USD 850 weekly living stipend\
 , travel subsidy USD 400 to 800\, up to USD 200 materials shipping reimbur
 sement\, plus room and board\, housing in historic log cabins\, and studio
  space USD 25 non-refundable application fee (fee waiver available on requ
 est)\nDuration: 2 to 6 weeks depending on session\n\nMore: https://loghave
 n.org/residencies/apply/
URL:https://loghaven.org/residencies/apply/
LOCATION:Knoxville\, Tennessee\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:prisma-art-prize-20th-edition-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260910
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260911
SUMMARY:Deadline: Prisma Art Prize 20th Edition
DESCRIPTION:The Prisma Art Prize is an international award for painting and
  two-dimensional artistic research based in Rome. The 20th edition selects
  emerging and established artists working in painting\, drawing\, illustra
 tion\, printmaking\, and traditional mixed media for a group exhibition at
  Palazzo Merulana\, opening November 5\, 2026. Winners share an annual cas
 h fund of EUR 2\,000 distributed across quarterly calls and receive inclus
 ion in the collective catalogue plus artist interviews. Additional opportu
 nities include solo exhibition prizes and fully funded placements at partn
 er art residencies. The prize is open internationally to all living artist
 s regardless of age\, gender\, nationality\, or educational background. Th
 e submission deadline for this edition is September 10\, 2026.\n\nOrganisa
 tion: Prisma Art Prize\nLocation: Rome\, Italy\nAward: EUR 2\,000 annual c
 ash fund distributed across quarterly winners\, plus group exhibition at P
 alazzo Merulana\, inclusion in the collective catalogue\, artist interview
 s\, and eligibility for solo show prizes (Isorrophia Gallery\, Pallavicini
 -Dettori) and partner art residencies (Dar Meso\, Casacon\, Osservatorioma
 ree) EUR 34 entry fee for 1 to 3 artworks\, plus EUR 5 for each additional
  artwork up to a maximum of 8\nDuration: Group exhibition runs November 5 
 to 8\, 2026\n\nMore: https://www.prismaartprize.com/
URL:https://www.prismaartprize.com/
LOCATION:Rome\, Italy
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:hayama-artist-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260930
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261001
SUMMARY:Deadline: Hayama Artist Residency
DESCRIPTION:The Hayama Artist Residency introduces visual artists from arou
 nd the world to Japanese culture and offers them their first gallery exhib
 ition in Japan. The four-week residency takes place in Hayama\, a coastal 
 town in Kanagawa Prefecture about 1.5 hours from Tokyo. Selected artists r
 eceive roundtrip airfare to Tokyo\, shared accommodation with one other re
 sident\, and USD 800 for meals and local transportation. A core element is
  a group exhibition during the stay\, hosted in partnership with KOKI ARTS
 \, a contemporary gallery in the Bakurocho art district of Tokyo. The prog
 ram is open to visual artists over 21 working in any medium\, based anywhe
 re in the world\, and applications are reviewed by the director and an int
 ernational selection committee. The June 2027 cycle has an application dea
 dline of September 30\, 2026\, with notification by December 15\, 2026.\n\
 nOrganisation: Hayama Artist Residency\nLocation: Hayama\, Kanagawa Prefec
 ture\, Japan\nAward: Fully funded: roundtrip airfare to Tokyo (Narita or H
 aneda)\, shared accommodation for 4 weeks\, and USD 800 for meals and loca
 l transportation. Group exhibition at KOKI ARTS gallery in Tokyo. USD 95 a
 pplication fee for first-time applicants\nDuration: 4 weeks\n\nMore: https
 ://www.hayamaresidency.com/
URL:https://www.hayamaresidency.com/
LOCATION:Hayama\, Kanagawa Prefecture\, Japan
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:studios-at-mass-moca-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261101
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261102
SUMMARY:Deadline: The Studios at MASS MoCA Residencies
DESCRIPTION:The Studios at MASS MoCA is a year-round residency program on t
 he museum's campus in North Adams\, Massachusetts\, hosting up to 10 artis
 ts at a time for stays of two or four weeks. It primarily welcomes visual 
 artists across all media and writers in all literary disciplines\, and app
 licants from around the world are encouraged to apply. Residents receive 2
 4-hour access to a private furnished studio\, lodging in nearby apartments
 \, and several communal meals each week\, plus museum membership benefits 
 and access to The Clark Art Institute. The program offers need-based finan
 cial aid (artists typically pay between USD 0 and USD 450 per week) and fu
 lly funded fellowships that cover all residency fees for up to four weeks.
  General application deadlines fall on May 1 and November 1 each year\, an
 d the application is free to submit.\n\nOrganisation: MASS MoCA (Massachus
 etts Museum of Contemporary Art)\nLocation: North Adams\, Massachusetts\, 
 USA\nAward: Provides private 24/7 studio space\, furnished housing\, and s
 even communal meals per week. Financial aid is available so artists reques
 ting it typically pay between USD 0 and USD 450 per week\, and fully funde
 d fellowships cover all residency fees for up to four weeks. Artists who f
 ully self-fund pay a subsidized rate of USD 650 per week.\nDuration: 2 or 
 4 weeks\n\nMore: https://massmoca.org/studios/
URL:https://massmoca.org/studios/
LOCATION:North Adams\, Massachusetts\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:rauschenberg-medical-emergency-grants-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261117
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261118
SUMMARY:Deadline: Rauschenberg Medical Emergency Grants
DESCRIPTION:The Rauschenberg Medical Emergency Grants\, administered by the
  New York Foundation for the Arts on behalf of the Robert Rauschenberg Fou
 ndation\, provide one-time grants of up to USD 5\,000 to help artists in f
 inancial need cover recent unexpected medical\, dental\, and mental health
  emergencies. The program is open to generative visual and media artists a
 nd choreographers working in visual arts\, film\, video\, electronic and d
 igital arts\, and choreography who live anywhere in the United States\, th
 e District of Columbia\, a Tribal Nation\, or a U.S. Territory. Applicants
  must be artists in financial need\, with adjusted gross income at or belo
 w USD 80\,000 for an individual or USD 160\,000 for joint filers\, and mus
 t not have received a Rauschenberg Medical or Dancer Emergency Grant in th
 e past five years. Eligible expenses include emergency medical bills\, dia
 gnostics\, consultations\, therapy\, prescription medications\, emergency 
 dental care\, and transportation to appointments. The grant does not cover
  lost wages\, general living expenses\, or care for anyone other than the 
 artist. Applications are accepted during defined cycles\, with the current
  cycle running roughly from late October to mid November.\n\nOrganisation:
  New York Foundation for the Arts (NYFA) / Robert Rauschenberg Foundation\
 nLocation: United States (remote application)\nAward: One-time grants up t
 o USD 5\,000\nDuration: One-time grant\n\nMore: https://www.nyfa.org/award
 s-grants/rauschenberg-medical-emergency-grants/
URL:https://www.nyfa.org/awards-grants/rauschenberg-medical-emergency-grant
 s/
LOCATION:United States (remote application)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:a-wrinkle-in-thyme-farm-fiber-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261231
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270101
SUMMARY:Deadline: Farm\, Flock and Fiber Artist in Residence
DESCRIPTION:A Wrinkle in Thyme Farm is a small\, women-owned diversified fa
 rm in Sumner\, Maine that offers a six-month live-in fiber arts residency 
 starting in May. The resident exchanges an average of 15 to 20 hours per w
 eek of farm work for a modest monthly stipend\, free private rustic housin
 g\, community meals\, farm-grown food\, and access to the fiber studio. Re
 sidents receive solo studio time plus one day a week of learning and colla
 boration with fiber artist Marty Elkin\, working with home-grown Maine woo
 l through felting\, dyeing\, knitting and spinning. The program also inclu
 des training in flock management\, animal husbandry and lamb care\, with t
 he option to add two months for lambing season. It is designed for emergin
 g fiber artists who are single females able to lift 50 pounds and work aro
 und a farm. Applications open in November with a December 31 deadline and 
 a non-refundable USD 25 application fee.\n\nOrganisation: A Wrinkle in Thy
 me Farm\nLocation: Sumner\, Maine\, USA\nAward: Modest monthly stipend (ar
 ound USD 400/month) in exchange for roughly 15 to 20 hours/week of farm wo
 rk\, plus free rustic private housing (solar power\, wood stove)\, shared 
 kitchen\, bath and WiFi\, community meals and farm-grown food\, dedicated 
 solo studio time\, and weekly collaboration with resident fiber artist Mar
 ty Elkin. USD 25 non-refundable application fee\nDuration: Six months begi
 nning in May\, with an optional two additional months for lambing and earl
 y lamb care\n\nMore: https://www.awrinkleinthymefarm.com/?page_id=1294
URL:https://www.awrinkleinthymefarm.com/?page_id=1294
LOCATION:Sumner\, Maine\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:kala-fellowship-program-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20270301
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270302
SUMMARY:Deadline: Kala Fellowship Program
DESCRIPTION:The Kala Fellowship Program supports international\, national\,
  and local artists producing innovative work in and across multiple media\
 , with an emphasis on Kala's specialized printmaking\, photography\, and d
 igital media equipment. The institute supports up to 6 artists per cycle w
 ith a USD 3\,000 stipend\, 24/7 access to its Berkeley facilities for 1 to
  9 months\, one month of housing for artists based outside the 9 Bay Area 
 counties\, a Kala class or workshop\, and a culminating group show in the 
 Kala Gallery. Applications are submitted through kala.slideroom.com and re
 quire a statement of interest\, an artist CV\, documentation of 5 to 10 re
 cent works\, and two references. Artists enrolled in a degree-granting pro
 gram during the fellowship period are not eligible. The application opens 
 in December with no fee through January 15\, after which a USD 25 applicat
 ion fee applies through the March 1 deadline.\n\nOrganisation: Kala Art In
 stitute\nLocation: Berkeley\, California\, USA\nAward: USD 3\,000 stipend\
 , 24/7 facility access for 1 to 9 months\, 1 month of housing for artists 
 outside the 9 Bay Area counties\, a Kala class or workshop\, and a group e
 xhibition USD 25 application fee (free if applying December through Januar
 y 15)\nDuration: 1 to 9 months within the July 2026 to June 2027 fellowshi
 p period\n\nMore: https://www.kala.org/residencies/fellowship-program/
URL:https://www.kala.org/residencies/fellowship-program/
LOCATION:Berkeley\, California\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:roswell-artist-in-residence-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20270315
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20270316
SUMMARY:Deadline: Roswell Artist-in-Residence Program
DESCRIPTION:The Roswell Artist-in-Residence Program\, established in 1967 a
 nd run by The RAiR Foundation\, offers visual artists a year-long studio-b
 ased residency known as the Gift of Time. Each resident receives a private
  house and a studio on a fifty-acre complex\, with rent\, utilities\, repa
 irs\, and maintenance covered by the program. Artists also receive a month
 ly stipend of USD 1\,100 plus a USD 250 monthly materials stipend. The pro
 gram is open to professional visual artists aged 21 and older working in p
 ainting\, drawing\, sculpture\, printmaking\, photography\, video\, digita
 l media\, and installation. It does not support performance art\, writing\
 , music\, or production crafts. The application period for the next cycle 
 runs from January 1 to March 15\, 2027\, and international applicants are 
 accepted with visa support available.\n\nOrganisation: The RAiR Foundation
 \nLocation: Roswell\, New Mexico\, USA\nAward: USD 1\,100 per month stipen
 d\, plus USD 250 per month materials stipend from the Frederick Hammersley
  Foundation. Includes a private house and a studio with rent\, utilities\,
  repairs\, and maintenance covered. USD 26.32 application fee\nDuration: 1
 2 months (one year)\n\nMore: https://www.rair.org/application-info
URL:https://www.rair.org/application-info
LOCATION:Roswell\, New Mexico\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:cmrfe-multispecies-residency-autumn-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260705
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260706
SUMMARY:Deadline: Artist Residency Autumn 2026 (Centre for Multispecies Rel
 ations and Future Ecologies\, Palermo)
DESCRIPTION:The Centre for Multispecies Relations and Future Ecologies invi
 tes applications from two artists for a 62-day residency (12 October - 12 
 December 2026) at its site in the Altarello di Baida district of Palermo\,
  Sicily. The residency is structured around a 1\,500 sqm garden at the thr
 eshold between the city's urban expansion and the historic rural landscape
  of the surrounding hills\; the site\, degraded through previous use (soil
  compaction and significant biodiversity loss)\, functions as both studio 
 and subject\, and artists participate in an ongoing process of ecological 
 transformation\, producing interventions that emerge from extended observa
 tion and fieldwork. Applications are welcome across all mediums and discip
 lines (installation\, sound\, performance\, video\, food art\, participato
 ry practice\, and beyond)\; research-based and interdisciplinary practices
  are especially encouraged. The Centre works at the intersection of art\, 
 science\, and (agro)ecological practices\, with a focus on multispecies co
 existence and climate change in the Mediterranean\, and has been based in 
 Palermo since 2021. PROGRAMME: five phases (orientation with small trips a
 nd gatherings\; observation with independent fieldwork and consultations w
 ith artists\, curators\, scientists\, and anthropologists\; proposal and e
 cological feasibility developed with mentors\; creation\; and public resti
 tution with an open event\, a workshop\, and a public discussion). Each ar
 tist develops an independent site-specific intervention\; the two resident
 s share the site\, living space\, and process\, with exchange encouraged b
 ut not prescribed. Artist duos and artists who want to collaborate are enc
 ouraged to apply (you can apply as an individual for one position\, as a d
 uo for both\, or as two artists collaborating for two positions). Mentorsh
 ip by co-founders/artistic directors Fabio Aranzulla and Luca Cinquemani (
 weekly site visits\, studio discussions\, work-in-progress presentations)\
 ; logistics managed by Francesca Farris. WHO: artists whose work engages w
 ith ecology\, multispecies relations\, or the more-than-human\, who can mo
 ve between observation and making and are interested in dialogue with scie
 ntists\, land workers\, and local communities. Priority is given to artist
 s from working-class and less-privileged backgrounds\, those who self-iden
 tify as part of marginalised communities\, and candidates reflecting diver
 sity in gender\, age\, geographical background\, and ability\; green trave
 l is prioritised as a condition of participation where feasible. Applicant
 s should be open to living and working in a neighbourhood on the margins o
 f Palermo's periphery. Funded by Culture Moves Europe (Creative Europe pro
 gramme of the European Union). APPLICATION: first phase via the online for
 m (opened 10 June)\; shortlisted artists contacted before the end of July\
 ; second phase is video calls with shortlisted candidates\; applications a
 ccepted in English and Italian. Contact: contact.cmrfe@gmail.com. Deadline
  5 July 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Centre for Multispecies Relations and Futur
 e Ecologies\nLocation: Altarello di Baida district\, Palermo\, Sicily\, It
 aly. On-site 62-day residency\, 12 October - 12 December 2026. Open to all
  nationalities\, but applicants must be officially residing in a Creative 
 Europe country (excluding Italy).\nAward: Total allowance of EUR 1\,860 (b
 efore tax) per artist\, plus a travel budget of EUR 400 per artist (for di
 stances under 4\,000 km) with a EUR 400 green-mobility top-up\, plus a pro
 duction budget. Also provided: on-site accommodation in a fully furnished 
 independent house (private bedroom\; shared kitchen\, living room\, two ba
 throoms\; outdoor studio space 100m from the working site)\, access to rec
 ycled/salvaged materials through the Centre's partnerships\, a bicycle per
  resident\, and a final public event.\nDuration: 62-day residency\, 12 Oct
 ober - 12 December 2026\, structured in five phases (orientation\, observa
 tion/fieldwork\, proposal and ecological feasibility\, creation\, and publ
 ic restitution).\n\nMore: https://tally.so/r/81r5Mz
URL:https://tally.so/r/81r5Mz
LOCATION:Altarello di Baida district\, Palermo\, Sicily\, Italy. On-site 62
 -day residency\, 12 October - 12 December 2026. Open to all nationalities\
 , but applicants must be officially residing in a Creative Europe country 
 (excluding Italy).
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:upe-foundation-curatorial-fellowship-camden-art-centre-2026@artificialn
 ouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260713
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260714
SUMMARY:Deadline: Upe Foundation Curatorial Fellowship at Camden Art Centre
  2026
DESCRIPTION:Upe Foundation is launching the Upe Foundation Curatorial Fello
 wship at Camden Art Centre as part of its Fall 2026 Curatorial Fellowship 
 Programme. The opportunity invites Baltic early-career curators to apply f
 or a full-time curatorial role at Camden Art Centre\, an institution inter
 nationally acclaimed for its rigorous exhibitions\, residencies\, events a
 nd learning programmes. The fellowship is a full-time\, 12-month position 
 starting Autumn 2026\, with the possibility of a further 6-month extension
  (18 months total) upon review and mutual decision\; relocation to London 
 is required. ROLE: embedded within Camden Art Centre's Exhibitions Departm
 ent\, the Fellow works as Assistant Curator\, supporting the development\,
  coordination and delivery of the exhibitions programme and related projec
 ts and events\, with practical experience across exhibition research\, pro
 duction\, interpretation\, publications\, public programmes\, loans\, inst
 allation and documentation\, and liaising with artists\, galleries\, lende
 rs\, partner organisations\, writers and designers. The Fellow also shares
  research connected to Baltic and broader Central Eastern European artisti
 c contexts. ELIGIBILITY: a demonstrated connection to or sustained engagem
 ent with the Baltic region (Lithuania\, Latvia\, Estonia\, or their diaspo
 ras)\, which may include lived experience\, heritage\, working knowledge o
 f a Baltic language\, relevant research\, or curatorial work with Baltic a
 rtists/institutions/contexts\; early-career curatorial experience (freelan
 ce\, self-organised\, project-based or institutional)\; and a higher educa
 tion qualification (BA\, MA or equivalent) in curating\, art history\, vis
 ual culture or related disciplines. Desirable: working knowledge of Lithua
 nian\, Latvian or Estonian\; fluency in a second language\; experience wit
 h Articheck and with CRM systems (particularly Salesforce). Applicants mus
 t hold the right to work in the UK (via the under-26 'new entrant' Skilled
  Worker route\, the Creative Worker visa route\, or existing right to work
  such as British citizenship or settled/pre-settled status). OFFER: GBP 30
 \,960 salary\, structured professional development within the Exhibitions 
 team\, and opportunities to build professional networks in London and inte
 rnationally. Applications reviewed jointly by Upe Foundation and Camden Ar
 t Centre\, with first-round online interviews and a second interview for f
 inalists. The organizers strongly encourage applicants to write materials 
 in their own words and avoid generic or AI-generated responses. TIMELINE: 
 application deadline 12:00 noon UK time\, Monday 13 July 2026\; interviews
  6 August 2026\; final decision mid-August 2026\; start Autumn 2026. Quest
 ions: recruitment@camdenartcentre.org.\n\nOrganisation: Upe Foundation (in
  partnership with Camden Art Centre)\nLocation: London\, United Kingdom. F
 ull-time\, in-person\; relocation to London is required. Applicants must h
 old the right to work in the UK.\nAward: Salary of GBP 30\,960 per year. A
  full-time Assistant Curator role on a 12-month fixed-term contract\, with
  the possibility of a further 6-month extension (18 months total) subject 
 to formal review and mutual agreement.\nDuration: 12-month fixed-term posi
 tion starting Autumn 2026\, with possible 6-month extension (18 months tot
 al).\n\nMore: https://upefoundation.org/news/open-call-upe-foundation-cura
 torial-fellowship-at-camden-art-centre
URL:https://upefoundation.org/news/open-call-upe-foundation-curatorial-fell
 owship-at-camden-art-centre
LOCATION:London\, United Kingdom. Full-time\, in-person\; relocation to Lon
 don is required. Applicants must hold the right to work in the UK.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:galerie-tic-open-call-2027-galerie-mladych@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260720
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260721
SUMMARY:Deadline: Open Call 2027: Galerie mladych (Galerie TIC Brno)
DESCRIPTION:Galerie TIC announces an open call for exhibition projects for 
 Galerie mladych (Gallery of Young Artists) for the year 2027. Applicants s
 hould send a completed application form\, a project description with visua
 l documentation\, and an artist's portfolio with CV by midnight on 20 July
  2026 via the online form. THE GALLERY OFFERS: to cover the financial cost
 s of exhibition installation\; an artist/curator fee\; collection and tran
 sport of the exhibition\; and basic PR (photodocumentation included). APPL
 ICATION: the application form\, a short description and visual documentati
 on of the artistic/curatorial project\, and a portfolio with CV. Results w
 ill be published on the gallery's website and social media no later than t
 he end of August 2026. Deadline 20 July 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Galerie TIC
  Brno\nLocation: Brno\, Czech Republic. Exhibition projects realized at Ga
 lerie mladych during 2027.\nAward: The gallery covers the financial costs 
 of exhibition installation\, an artist/curator fee\, collection and transp
 ort of the exhibition\, and basic PR (photodocumentation included).\nDurat
 ion: Exhibition project for the year 2027.\n\nMore: https://galerie-tic.cz
 /en/open-call-2027-2
URL:https://galerie-tic.cz/en/open-call-2027-2
LOCATION:Brno\, Czech Republic. Exhibition projects realized at Galerie mla
 dych during 2027.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ted-posca-global-artist-residency-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: TED & POSCA Global Artist Residency 2026: Visible Mending
DESCRIPTION:TED (the global platform for ideas and storytelling) and POSCA 
 (a creative brand by uni Brands Corporation) are launching a new kind of a
 rtist residency: a globally distributed cohort of artists working across d
 ifferent geographies\, cultures\, and communities\, united by a shared dri
 ve to shape public life through art. Fine Acts\, the external curatorial p
 artner selected by TED & POSCA\, leads the curation\, creative direction\,
  and coordination. There is no single location and no central studio: sele
 cted artists work within their own communities\, following a shared creati
 ve constraint (a unifying conceptual framework around repair\, hope\, and 
 beauty)\, with projects unfolding in public space\, community participatio
 n as a key part of the work\, and process mattering as much as outcome. 20
 26 THEME\, VISIBLE MENDING: inspired in part by Kintsugi (the Japanese pra
 ctice of repairing broken ceramics with gold)\, the theme explores repair 
 as a creative and civic act\, inviting artists to consider how wounds\, ru
 ptures\, and imperfections can become sites of transformation\, and to mak
 e processes of repair visible through public interventions that spark refl
 ection\, dialogue\, and collective imagination. In 2026\, four artists wil
 l be selected to develop community-rooted public interventions to be imple
 mented in 2027. AWARD: each selected artist receives a total of USD 15\,00
 0 to cover artist fees\, production costs/community activation\, and docum
 entation\, plus a production budget and tools from POSCA\, creative direct
 ion and storytelling support\, and visibility through TED and Fine Acts' g
 lobal platforms. While the residency term is one year\, the initiative wil
 l run for multiple years (2027\, 2028\, 2029)\, expanding the cohort year 
 by year and building an evolving global archive of civic artistic interven
 tions. Apply by 31 July 2026.\n\nOrganisation: TED & POSCA (curated by Fin
 e Acts)\nLocation: Globally distributed\; no single location or central st
 udio. Selected artists work within their own communities\, with projects u
 nfolding in public space.\nAward: Each selected artist receives a total of
  USD 15\,000 (covering artist fees\, production costs/community activation
 \, and documentation)\, plus a production budget and tools from POSCA\, cr
 eative direction and storytelling support\, and visibility through TED and
  Fine Acts' global platforms.\nDuration: One-year residency term\; communi
 ty-rooted public interventions developed in 2026 for implementation in 202
 7. The initiative runs for multiple years (2027\, 2028\, 2029)\, expanding
  the cohort year by year.\n\nMore: https://fineacts.co/ted-posca-residency
URL:https://fineacts.co/ted-posca-residency
LOCATION:Globally distributed\; no single location or central studio. Selec
 ted artists work within their own communities\, with projects unfolding in
  public space.
END:VEVENT
