DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260731
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260801
SUMMARY:Deadline: Lee Ufan Arles: Prix Art & Environnement 2026 (Residency 
 + Exhibition Prize)
DESCRIPTION:The Prix Art & Environnement (4th edition)\, awarded by Lee Ufa
 n Arles and Maison Guerlain\, supports an artist working at the intersecti
 on of art and the natural environment. The prize winner receives a funded 
 6–8 week production residency in Arles in early 2027\, including product
 ion space\, accommodation\, and mentorship from Lee Ufan Arles staff\, cul
 minating in a solo summer 2027 exhibition. ELIGIBILITY: open to all artist
 s of any discipline and nationality\, with no age or degree requirements\;
  candidates must demonstrate at least one solo exhibition and one or more 
 group exhibitions. DEADLINE: 31 July 2026. APPLY via the Google Form linke
 d from the Lee Ufan Arles website.\n\nOrganisation: Lee Ufan Arles and Mai
 son Guerlain\nLocation: Arles\, France (residency and exhibition)\nAward: 
 Funded residency (production space + accommodation) in Arles. No cash priz
 e amount specified. No application fee.\nDuration: 6–8 weeks residency i
 n early 2027\, followed by a solo summer 2027 exhibition\n\nMore: https://
 en.leeufan-arles.org/evenements/art-environment-prize
URL:https://en.leeufan-arles.org/evenements/art-environment-prize
LOCATION:Arles\, France (residency and exhibition)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:vac-belgrade-visual-anthropology-residency@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20271231
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20280101
SUMMARY:Deadline: Visual Anthropology Center (VAC): Residency Programme (Be
 lgrade)
DESCRIPTION:Visual Anthropology Center (VAC) in Belgrade invites filmmakers
 \, visual anthropologists\, artists\, and researchers to apply for its res
 idency programme. The residency specialises in visual anthropology but is 
 also open to individual and collaborative projects in experimental ethnogr
 aphy\, creative documentary film\, and other artistic mediums. Residents m
 ay apply with a project aimed at a public showing\, or use the time and sp
 ace to reflect\, research\, or write without a specific outcome. WHAT IS P
 ROVIDED: accommodation and studio space in central Belgrade\; additional w
 orkspace and community connection through Community Center KROV (an indepe
 ndent creative hub hosting lectures\, events\, and exhibitions)\; project 
 guidance and mentorship from film professionals\, ethnomusicologists\, pro
 ducers\, artists\, curators\, and anthropologists\; connections to local c
 ultural and academic institutions\, archives\, galleries\, and exhibition 
 spaces\; access to camera equipment\, translators for fieldwork or editing
 \, fixers\, and project-specific services or materials\; opportunity to ex
 hibit a final project as an exhibition\, installation\, screening\, worksh
 op\, or lecture. Eligible projects may be promoted through VAC's platforms
  and partner networks\, including the Vizantrop Film Festival\, for region
 al and international visibility. ELIGIBILITY: filmmakers\, visual anthropo
 logists\, artists\, and researchers\; individual and collaborative project
 s welcome. Applications accepted on a rolling basis.\n\nOrganisation: Visu
 al Anthropology Center (VAC)\nLocation: Belgrade\, Serbia (accommodation a
 nd studio in central Belgrade\; additional workspace at Community Center K
 ROV)\nAward: EUR 1\,000–1\,500 per month (stipend\, varies by project re
 quirements)\, plus accommodation and studio space provided. No application
  fee.\nDuration: Approximately 1–2 months\; flexible packages depending 
 on project needs\n\nMore: https://vac.rs/program/residency
URL:https://vac.rs/program/residency
LOCATION:Belgrade\, Serbia (accommodation and studio in central Belgrade\; 
 additional workspace at Community Center KROV)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:wsw-artists-book-residency-grant-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20261115
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20261116
SUMMARY:Deadline: WSW Artist's Book Residency Grant
DESCRIPTION:Women's Studio Workshop (WSW) offers an eight- to ten-week resi
 dency for artists to produce a limited-edition artist's book. Working inte
 nsively in WSW's studios in Rosendale\, NY\, selected artists print and bi
 nd their own books\; edition size must be between 50 and 100 copies. AMOUN
 T: $350/week stipend\; up to $1\,000 for materials\; up to $250 for travel
  within the Continental US\; free onsite housing\; 24/7 studio access. WSW
  provides technical advice\, training on new equipment\, techniques\, and 
 materials\, and production assistance. SALES CONTRACT: 20% of the edition 
 goes to the artist\; 20% (at least nine copies) stays with WSW for archiva
 l and institutional sales\; 60% goes to general distribution and sale. If 
 the artist sells through WSW\, WSW takes a 30% commission plus 20% for mar
 keting\; the artist receives a 50% commission\, paid annually around 30 Ju
 ne. WSW holds the right to sell distribution copies at a 20% discount to s
 tanding-order and repository institutions. WSW's books are held in over 45
 0 collections worldwide\, including the Library of Congress\, Yale Univers
 ity\, and Vassar College. An outside jury of artists and curators selects 
 recipients. INDIGENOUS ARTISTS: applicants may check the appropriate box o
 n the Submittable form to be considered for the BIMA Artist's Book Residen
 cy Grant for Indigenous Artists. APPLICATION MATERIALS (upload via Submitt
 able): current resume\; brief project description including media required
  (200-word maximum)\; materials budget form (Google Sheets\, Excel\, or PD
 F)\; up to ten images of recent work\; image script (title\, medium\, dime
 nsions\, date). MAILED MATERIALS (to WSW at the address below): a physical
  book mock-up demonstrating how the book will be bound or function\, actua
 l size\, with at least 1-2 fully realised spreads\; and the shipping form 
 (download and open the PDF locally). Mail to: Artist's Book Application\, 
 Women's Studio Workshop\, PO Box 489\, Rosendale\, NY 12472. Applications 
 open 1 August 2026\; deadline 15 November 2026\, 11:59pm EST\; notificatio
 n March 2027\; residency runs September through June\, one year after appl
 ication. Apply via Submittable at https://wsworkshop.org/residencies/artis
 ts-book-residency-grant/.\n\nOrganisation: Women's Studio Workshop (WSW)\n
 Location: Rosendale\, NY\, USA\; in-person residency.\nAward: $350/week st
 ipend\; up to $1\,000 for materials\; up to $250 for travel within the Con
 tinental US\; free onsite housing\; 24/7 studio access. No application fee
 .\nDuration: 8-10 weeks\; residency runs September through June\, one year
  after application.\n\nMore: https://wsworkshop.org/residencies/artists-bo
 ok-residency-grant/
URL:https://wsworkshop.org/residencies/artists-book-residency-grant/
LOCATION:Rosendale\, NY\, USA\; in-person residency.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:samstag-international-visual-arts-scholarship-2027@artificialnouveau.gi
 thub.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260630
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260701
SUMMARY:Deadline: Samstag International Visual Arts Scholarships - Class of
  2027
DESCRIPTION:The Samstag International Visual Arts Scholarships are annual s
 cholarships enabling Australian artists to develop their artistic capaciti
 es through a dedicated year of practice-based learning at an international
  institution of their choice. AMOUNT: AUD $75\,000 tax-exempt stipend\; in
 stitutional fees for one academic year (where applicable)\; return airfare
 s\; and travel and health insurance. ELIGIBILITY: Australian citizens or p
 ermanent residents aged 18 or over who are either (a) currently enrolled i
 n a practice-led visual arts program at an Australian institution of highe
 r education\, having successfully completed at least two years of an under
 graduate or postgraduate degree\; or (b) graduates of a practice-led visua
 l arts undergraduate or postgraduate qualification at an Australian instit
 ution of higher education (graduates of more than five years' standing are
  now eligible following 2023 guideline updates). PROCESS: applicants must 
 create an account in the online portal\, download the Samstag Microsoft Po
 werPoint template\, read the Class of 2027 Guidelines\, and complete and s
 ubmit the online application form. Accounts can be created before the dead
 line and applications saved for later submission. Prior applicants (Classe
 s of 2024\, 2025\, or 2026) can reuse the same account. Deadline: 30 June 
 2026\, midnight Australian Central Standard Time (ACST). Apply at https://
 samstag.adelaide.edu.au/scholarship/apply/.\n\nOrganisation: Samstag Museu
 m of Art\, University of South Australia\nLocation: Australia (applicants 
 must be Australian citizens or permanent residents)\; 12-month placement a
 t an international institution of the scholar's choice.\nAward: AUD $75\,0
 00 tax-exempt stipend\; institutional fees for one academic year of study 
 (where applicable)\; return airfares\; and travel and health insurance. No
  application fee.\nDuration: 12 months overseas at an international learni
 ng institution.\n\nMore: https://samstag.adelaide.edu.au/scholarship/apply
 /
URL:https://samstag.adelaide.edu.au/scholarship/apply/
LOCATION:Australia (applicants must be Australian citizens or permanent res
 idents)\; 12-month placement at an international institution of the schola
 r's choice.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:freelands-learning-through-making-fund-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260626T212248Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260911
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260912
SUMMARY:Deadline: Freelands Foundation: Learning Through Making Fund
DESCRIPTION:The Learning Through Making fund supports UK-based visual art o
 rganisations to bring opportunities for making and material exploration in
 to their art education work. Freelands Foundation is looking for explorato
 ry projects that embrace openness\, collaboration\, and iteration -- enabl
 ing organisations to work with materials in an expansive way\, unpicking p
 reconceptions about making and material literacy without predefined outcom
 es. ELIGIBLE ACTIVITIES: providing materials\, transport\, or access to ex
 pertise and facilities\; action-research trials such as a new series of wo
 rkshops or events developing material literacy\; adding a making-focused e
 lement to existing activity. Projects may range from a few days to several
  months\, but must take place between 1 January and 31 December 2027. AMOU
 NT: up to £25\,000\; funding provided no earlier than December 2026. ELIG
 IBILITY: UK-based visual art organisations run with a charitable purpose a
 nd for public benefit\; eligible types include charities registered in Eng
 land and Wales\, Scotland\, or Northern Ireland\; exempt charities\; galle
 ries\, museums\, or organisations within a Local Authority or larger chari
 table body (e.g. universities)\; and Community Interest Companies or Commu
 nity Benefit Societies meeting specific criteria (charitable purposes\, as
 set lock\, no dividend distribution\, ability to segregate restricted fund
 s). Organisations with a prior Freelands Foundation grant relationship are
  eligible\; you may not apply for activity already funded by Freelands Fou
 ndation. Individuals are not eligible. HOW TO APPLY: download the Applicat
 ion Form\, Application Guidance\, and optional Access Form from freelandsf
 oundation.co.uk\; email completed form to grants@freelandsfoundation.co.uk
  with subject line 'LTM Fund - Application'\; one additional page of image
 s or diagrams may be included. APPLICATION SUPPORT SESSIONS (online): 9 Ju
 ly 2026\, 10:30am-12pm\; 12 August 2026\, 10:30am-12pm. KEY DATES: applica
 tions open 17 June 2026\; close 11 September 2026 at 12pm\; outcomes share
 d 23 November 2026.\n\nOrganisation: Freelands Foundation\nLocation: UK (E
 ngland\, Northern Ireland\, Scotland\, Wales)\; activity must occur within
  the United Kingdom.\nAward: Up to £25\,000. No application fee.\nDuratio
 n: Projects of any length\, taking place between 1 January and 31 December
  2027. Funding provided no earlier than December 2026.\n\nMore: https://fr
 eelandsfoundation.co.uk/engage/apply/grants/learning-through-making-fund
URL:https://freelandsfoundation.co.uk/engage/apply/grants/learning-through-
 making-fund
LOCATION:UK (England\, Northern Ireland\, Scotland\, Wales)\; activity must
  occur within the United Kingdom.
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
